94":"1394","1360":"1360","abt 1345":"about 1345","Abt 1350":"about 1350","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1367":"1367","1345":"1345","ABT 1320":"about 1320","1343":"1343","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1287":"1287","1331":"1331","1320":"1320","1428":"1428","1328":"1328","Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Hambleton, Yorkshire, England":"Hambleton, Yorkshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Checkenden, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marmion","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: perhaps an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name. Compare   Merriman  .","English (Lancashire; of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Old French <i>marmion</i> ‘monkey, brat’."],"variants":[{"name":"Merriman","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>mirie</i>, <i>merie</i>, <i>murie</i> ‘merry, pleasant’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Merry   1. This surname is established in Ireland (perhaps as an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name; compare   Marmion  ) as well as England.","there has probably been some confusion with <b>Marriman</b>, probably an occupational name meaning ‘servant of <i>Mary</i>’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’, or perhaps a pet form of <i>Mary</i> using the hypocoristic suffix -<i>man</i>. The surname <i>Marriman</i> is now vanishingly rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marmon","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Gloucestershire):","variant of   Marmion  .","variant of <b>Marriman</b>, an occupational name meaning ‘servant of Mary’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":8,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":17,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Marmion was born about 1320, in Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas Marmion, was 35 and her mother, Agnes, was 23. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with William Harlyungrugge. She died about 1367, in her hometown, at the age of 49, and was buried in Hambleton, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"ABT 1320–ABT 1367":"umbes 1320–umbes 1367","1320–1367":"1320–1367","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1331–1367":"1331–1367","1315–1394":"1315–1394","1343–1428":"1343–1428","134